      <p class="mt-5 !font-light md:text-xl text-base-content">In Bonfire, in order to edit an existing extension and test the changes you need to properly include the extension in the development process. The process is quite straightforward:</p>
      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-4xl text-center font-bold tracking-tight !leading-normal mb-10 text-base-content">Cloning the extension</h2>
      <p class="mt-5 !font-light md:text-xl text-base-content">
        Use <code>just dep-clone *dep* *repo*</code> to clone an extension from its Git repository. Replace <i>dep</i> with the extension name and <i>repo</i> with the full url. The cloned extension will be cloned in <code>./extensions</code>. The folder will include all the needed files, included the <code>.git</code> folder.
       <br/>Example:</p>
       
       {% highlight "bash" %}
       just dep-clone-local bonfire_me https://github.com/bonfire-networks/bonfire_me
        {% endhighlight %}

      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-4xl text-center font-bold tracking-tight !leading-normal mb-10 text-base-content">Enabling the Extension</h2>
      <p class="mt-5 !font-light md:text-xl text-base-content">
        After cloning, choose to use the local version by editing <code>./config/deps.path</code> (create it if it doesn’t exist). <br/>
        The format to follow is the following: <code>dep_name = "dep_path" </code>.<br/>
        To disable a local extension, comment or delete its line in .deps.path.<br/>
        Use just dev to run the app with changes hot-reloading.
      </p>
      {% highlight "bash" %}
      # ./config/deps.path
bonfire_me = "./extensions/bonfire_me"
# bonfire_boundaries = "./extensions/bonfire_boundaries" ### disabled extension
      {% endhighlight %}


